SENATE BILL 412
J1 6lr1618
CF HB 658
By: Senator Augustine
Introduced and read first time: January 29, 2026
Assigned to: Finance and Judicial Proceedings
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted with floor amendments
Read second time: March 6, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Maryland Department of Health – Forensic Review Boards and Community
3 Forensic Aftercare Program – Established
4 FOR the purpose of repealing the requirement that a forensic review board provide notice
5 to certain individuals within a certain time period after issuing a recommendation
6 to the court; authorizing an authorized agent to attend a forensic review board
7 meeting virtually; establishing the Community Forensic Aftercare Program in the
8 Maryland Department of Health to monitor committed persons on conditional
9 release and individuals with mental illness or intellectual disability who are
10 required to be monitored under certain circumstances; requiring the Program to
11 establish a community monitoring board to make certain decisions and
12 recommendations related to conditional release and out–of–state travel; and
13 generally relating to forensic review boards and the Community Forensic Aftercare
14 Program.
15 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
16 Article – Criminal Procedure
17 Section 3–101(a), (b), and (d) and 3–121(b)
18 Annotated Code of Maryland
19 (2025 Replacement Volume)
20 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
21 Article – Criminal Procedure
22 Section 3–122(a) 3–120.1
23 Annotated Code of Maryland
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0412*

2 SENATE BILL 412
1 (2025 Replacement Volume)
2 BY adding to
3 Article – Health – General
4 Section 13–5901 through 13–5904 to be under the new subtitle “Subtitle 59.
5 Community Forensic Aftercare Program”
6 Annotated Code of Maryland
7 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
8 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
9 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
10 Article – Criminal Procedure
11 3–101.
12 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
13 (b) “Committed person” means a person committed to the Health Department as
14 not criminally responsible under the test for criminal responsibility.
15 (d) “Health Department” means the Maryland Department of Health.
16 3–120.1.
17 (a) In this section, “authorized agent” means an individual who is not counsel for
18 the committed person and who is selected by the committed person to represent the
19 interests of the committed person in all forensic review board matters.
20 (b) (1) The Health Department shall establish a forensic review board at each
21 facility that has charge of a committed person under this subtitle.
22 (2) A forensic review board may make recommendations relating to the
23 release or rehabilitation of a committed person under this subtitle.
24 (c) Each member of a forensic review board shall be a health care provider
25 licensed under the Health Occupations Article.
26 (d) (1) At least once each year, each forensic review board shall review each
27 committed person’s eligibility for release under § 3–114 of this subtitle.
28 (2) The forensic review board shall, by a majority vote of the members,
29 determine whether to recommend to the court that a committed person is eligible for
30 discharge or conditional release, with or without proposed conditions.
31 (3) (i) Each forensic review board shall maintain a written record
32 containing its findings and recommendations.

SENATE BILL 412 3
1 (ii) The written record shall be included in the medical record of the
2 committed person.
3 (iii) The findings shall include the reasons for the forensic review
4 board’s recommendation and a plan for overcoming any barriers to release.
5 (4) When making a recommendation under this section, a forensic review
6 board shall consider a written statement offered by the committed person to the forensic
7 review board.
8 (5) The forensic review board shall provide notice to a committed person
9 and the counsel of record for the committed person[:
10 (i)] at least 10 days before the forensic review board holds a meeting
11 concerning the committed person[; and
12 (ii) within 10 days after the forensic review board issues a
13 recommendation to the court].
14 (e) (1) Each forensic review board shall have an odd number of members.
15 (2) Each member of the forensic review board shall have one vote.
16 (3) (i) A forensic review board may not conduct a review under
17 subsection (d) of this section unless a quorum is present.
18 (ii) A majority of the members of the forensic review board is a
19 quorum.
20 (f) (1) A committed person may appoint an authorized agent to attend the
21 [portion] ENTIRETY of a forensic review board meeting concerning the committed person,
22 EXCEPT FOR THE FINAL VOTING PORTION OF A MEETING.
23 (2) An authorized agent may be a social worker or a nonlegal
24 representative employed by the office of the attorney representing the committed person.
25 (3) An authorized agent may only give and hear arguments.
26 (4) AN AUTHORIZED AGENT MAY ATTEND A FORENSIC REVIEW BOARD
27 MEETING VIRTUALLY.
28 [(4)] (5) Counsel for any party may not attend forensic review board
29 meetings.

4 SENATE BILL 412
1 (g) (1) If the committed person’s treatment team determines that the
2 committed person is eligible for discharge or conditional release before the annual review
3 scheduled under subsection (d) of this section, the treatment team shall notify the forensic
4 review board in writing of the need for a release eligibility review.
5 (2) Within 30 days after receiving notice under paragraph (1) of this
6 subsection, the forensic review board shall conduct a review in accordance with subsection
7 (d) of this section.
8 (3) The treatment team shall provide a written statement that includes the
9 clinical reasons underlying the determination that the committed person is eligible for
10 discharge or conditional release.
11 (4) A copy of the notification made under paragraph (1) of this subsection
12 and the written statement required under paragraph (3) of this subsection shall be included
13 in the medical record of the committed person.
14 (h) A copy of a document or record produced by a forensic review board under this
15 section shall, on request, be provided to:
16 (1) the committed person;
17 (2) counsel for the committed person;
18 (3) the court;
19 (4) the State’s Attorney; or
20 (5) the Health Department.
21 (i) The committed person’s treatment team shall implement recommendations, if
22 any, from the forensic review board and make arrangements for necessary treatment to
23 rehabilitate the committed person in accordance with § 10–706 of the Health – General
24 Article.
25 (j) (1) A forensic review board may appoint a representative to testify as to
26 the Health Department’s position at a release hearing.
27 (2) If a forensic review board takes a position contrary to the position of the
28 committed person’s treatment team, the representative appointed under this subsection
29 may not be a member of the committed person’s treatment team.
30 (k) The Health Department shall adopt regulations to carry out this section.
31 3–121.

SENATE BILL 412 5
1 (b) (1) If a court receives a report that alleges that a committed person has
2 violated a condition of a conditional release, the court promptly shall:
3 (i) notify:
4 1. the Health Department;
5 2. counsel of record for the committed person; and
6 3. the State’s Attorney; and
7 (ii) provide the State’s Attorney with the name, address, and
8 telephone number of the person who reported the violation and a copy of the order for
9 conditional release.
10 (2) If the Health Department receives a report that alleges that a
11 committed person has violated conditional release, the Department shall:
12 (i) notify:
13 1. the court;
14 2. counsel of record for the committed person; and
15 3. the State’s Attorney; and
16 (ii) provide the State’s Attorney with the name, address, and
17 telephone number of the person who reported the violation and a copy of the order for
18 conditional release.
19 3–122.
20 (a) (1) An application to the court for a change in conditional release of a
21 committed person may be made by:
22 (i) the Health Department, THE COMMUNITY FORENSIC
23 AFTERCARE PROGRAM, or the State’s Attorney at any time; or
24 (ii) the committed person not earlier than 6 months after the court
25 ordered the conditional release, unless the court for good cause permits an earlier
26 application.
27 (2) The applicant for a change in conditional release shall notify the court
28 and other parties, in writing, of the application and the reasons for the requested change.

6 SENATE BILL 412
1 (3) On request by any party, the court shall hold a hearing after an
2 application is made under this subsection to determine whether the applicant has satisfied
3 the requirements for release under § 3–114 of this title.
4 Article – Health – General
5 SUBTITLE 59. COMMUNITY FORENSIC AFTERCARE PROGRAM.
6 13–5901.
7 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
8 INDICATED.
9 (B) “AUTHORIZED AGENT” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS NOT COUNSEL
10 FOR THE COMMITTED PERSON AND WHO IS SELECTED BY THE COMMITTED PERSON
11 TO REPRESENT THE INTERESTS OF THE COMMITTED PERSON IN ALL COMMUNITY
12 MONITORING BOARD MATTERS.
13 (C) “COMMITTED PERSON” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 3–101 OF THE
14 CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE.
15 (D) “MENTAL HEALTH TEAM” MEANS THE COMMITTED PERSON’S
16 INPATIENT BEHAVIORAL HEALTH PROVIDERS AND OUTPATIENT COMMUNITY
17 BEHAVIORAL HEALTH PROVIDERS.
18 (E) “PROGRAM” MEANS THE COMMUNITY FORENSIC AFTERCARE
19 PROGRAM.
20 (F) “PROGRAM MONITOR” MEANS A LICENSED CERTIFIED SOCIAL
21 WORKER–CLINICAL WORKER EMPLOYED BY THE PROGRAM TO:
22 (1) COLLECT AND REVIEW INFORMATION PERTAINING TO A
23 COMMITTED PERSON’S COMPLIANCE WITH A CONDITIONAL RELEASE ORDER; AND
24 (2) MAKE BEHAVIORAL HEALTH RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE
25 COMMITTED PERSON’S BEHAVIORAL HEALTH PROVIDERS AND THE COURT.
26 13–5902.
27 (A) THERE IS A COMMUNITY FORENSIC AFTERCARE PROGRAM IN THE
28 DEPARTMENT.
29 (B) THE PURPOSE OF THE PROGRAM IS TO MONITOR:

SENATE BILL 412 7
1 (1) COMMITTED PERSONS ON CONDITIONAL RELEASE; AND
2 (2) INDIVIDUALS WITH MENTAL ILLNESS OR INTELLECTUAL
3 DISABILITY WHO ARE REQUIRED TO BE MONITORED UNDER TITLE 3 OF THE
4 CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE.
5 (C) (1) THE PROGRAM SHALL:
6 (I) MONITOR COMMITTED PERSONS ON CONDITIONAL
7 RELEASE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE ORDER OF THE COURT UNDER TITLE 3 OF THE
8 CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE AND THE RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE
9 COMMITTED PERSON’S MENTAL HEALTH TEAM;
10 (II) MONITOR INDIVIDUALS WHO HAVE BEEN:
11 1. FOUND INCOMPETENT TO STAND TRIAL BUT NOT A
12 DANGER TO SELF OR THE PERSON OR PROPERTY OF OTHERS UNDER § 3–106 OF THE
13 CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE; AND
14 2. DISCHARGED FROM A DEPARTMENT FACILITY WITH A
15 RECOMMENDATION FOR RELEASED FROM CONFINEMENT IN A DEPARTMENT
16 FACILITY IN ACCORDANCE WITH A COURT ORDER FOR CONDITIONAL RELEASE THAT
17 REQUIRES COMMUNITY FORENSIC AFTERCARE MONITORING;
18 (III) MONITOR COMMITTED PERSONS ORDERED BY A COURT TO
19 BE CONDITIONALLY RELEASED UNDER § 3–114(C) OF THE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE
20 ARTICLE FOR COMPLIANCE WITH COURT ORDERED CONDITIONS OF RELEASE;
21 (IV) RECEIVE AND REPORT VIOLATIONS OF A CONDITION OF
22 CONDITIONAL RELEASE UNDER § 3–121 OF THE CRIMINAL LAW PROCEDURE
23 ARTICLE; AND
24 (V) (IV) FILE REVIEW APPLICATIONS FOR CHANGE IN
25 CONDITIONAL RELEASE ON BEHALF OF THE DEPARTMENT UNDER § 3–122 OF THE
26 CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE.
27 (2) THE PROGRAM:
28 (I) MAY NOT MAKE CLINICAL DECISIONS REGARDING THE
29 TREATMENT OF COMMITTED PERSONS; BUT
30 (II) MAY MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS REGARDING THE
31 TREATMENT OF THE COMMITTED PERSON.

8 SENATE BILL 412
1 (3) A HEALTH CARE PRACTITIONER–PATIENT RELATIONSHIP MAY
2 NOT BE DETERMINED TO EXIST BETWEEN A COMMITTED PERSON AND AN
3 INDIVIDUAL WHO MONITORS INDIVIDUALS OR PROVIDES OTHER SERVICES UNDER
4 THE PROGRAM.
5 (D) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, AT LEAST
6 ONCE EVERY 90 DAYS THREE TIMES WITHIN THE 6–MONTH PERIOD IMMEDIATELY
7 FOLLOWING THE DATE THE COMMITTED PERSON WAS INITIALLY RELEASED FROM A
8 FACILITY, A PROGRAM MONITOR SHALL HOLD A MEETING WITH:
9 (I) EACH COMMITTED PERSON MONITORED BY THE PROGRAM;
10 AND
11 (II) THE MENTAL HEALTH TEAM OF THE COMMITTED PERSON.
12 (2) BEGINNING 1 YEAR 6 MONTHS AFTER THE DATE THE COMMITTED
13 PERSON WAS RELEASED FROM A FACILITY, MEETINGS SHALL BE HELD AS
14 DETERMINED NECESSARY BY:
15 (I) THE MENTAL HEALTH TEAM OF THE COMMITTED PERSON;
16 OR
17 (II) AT THE REQUEST OF THE PROGRAM.
18 (3) A COMMITTED PERSON MAY APPOINT AN ADVOCATE, INCLUDING
19 A DESIGNEE OF COUNSEL OF THE COMMITTED PERSON, TO ATTEND A MEETING HELD
20 UNDER PARAGRAPHS (1) AND (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
21 (4) IF A MEETING UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OR (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION
22 CONCERNS THE COMMITTED PERSON’S COMPLIANCE WITH A CONDITIONAL
23 RELEASE, THE PROGRAM SHALL NOTIFY THE ADVOCATE OF THE COMMITTED
24 PERSON AND, IF APPLICABLE, THE DESIGNEE OF COUNSEL OF THE COMMITTED
25 PERSON OF THE MEETING.
26 (5) IF A MEETING UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OR (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION
27 IS HELD DUE TO AN EMERGENCY INVOLVING THE COMMITTED PERSON, THE
28 PROGRAM SHALL NOTIFY THE ADVOCATE OF THE COMMITTED PERSON AND, IF THE
29 COMMITTED PERSON HAS RETAINED COUNSEL, THE COUNSEL OF THE COMMITTED
30 PERSON OF THE CONTENT OF THE MEETING AS SOON AS PRACTICABLE.
31 (E) IF THE PROGRAM RECEIVES A REPORT ALLEGING THAT A COMMITTED
32 PERSON HAS VIOLATED CONDITIONAL RELEASE, THE PROGRAM SHALL:

SENATE BILL 412 9
1 (1) MAKE THE NOTIFICATIONS REQUIRED UNDER § 3–121(B)(2)(I) OF
2 THE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE;
3 (2) PROVIDE THE STATE’S ATTORNEY WITH THE INFORMATION
4 REQUIRED UNDER § 3–121(B)(2)(II) OF THE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE; AND
5 (3) IF APPLICABLE, PROVIDE TO THE COUNSEL OF RECORD FOR THE
6 COMMITTED PERSON THE INFORMATION PROVIDED UNDER ITEM (2) OF THIS
7 SUBSECTION.
8 (F) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, IF THE
9 PROGRAM RECEIVES A REQUEST FOR RECORDS FOR AN INDIVIDUAL WHO HAS
10 VIOLATED A CONDITION OF CONDITIONAL RELEASE AND A HEARING UNDER §
11 3–121(F) OF THE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE HAS BEEN SCHEDULED WITHIN
12 10 DAYS, THE PROGRAM SHALL PROVIDE THE RECORDS WITHIN 4 5 BUSINESS DAYS
13 AFTER THE REQUEST IS RECEIVED UNLESS THE PROGRAM IS PROHIBITED UNDER
14 APPLICABLE FEDERAL OR STATE LAW FROM DISCLOSING THE RECORDS TO THE
15 REQUESTING PERSON.
16 (2) (I) SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPHS (II) THROUGH (IV) OF THIS
17 PARAGRAPH IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 4–307(L) OF THIS ARTICLE, THE PROGRAM
18 AND ANY HEALTH CARE PROVIDER INVOLVED IN THE TREATMENT OF THE
19 INDIVIDUAL SHALL DISCLOSE ANY RECORDS WITHOUT THE AUTHORIZATION OF THE
20 INDIVIDUAL WHO IS THE SUBJECT OF THE RECORD TO A PUBLIC DEFENDER WHO
21 STATES IN WRITING THAT THE OFFICE OF THE PUBLIC DEFENDER REPRESENTS
22 THE INDIVIDUAL.
23 (II) LEGAL RECORDS REQUIRED TO BE DISCLOSED UNDER
24 SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH INCLUDE AN EMERGENCY PETITION.
25 (III) THE RECORDS DISCLOSED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF
26 THIS PARAGRAPH SHALL BE LIMITED TO THOSE RECORDS NEEDED BY THE PUBLIC
27 DEFENDER TO REPRESENT THE INDIVIDUAL.
28 (IV) RECORDS PROVIDED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS
29 SUBSECTION SHALL BE PROVIDED:
30 1. WITHIN 24 HOURS AFTER THE PROGRAM RECEIVES A
31 WRITTEN REQUEST FOR THE RECORDS FROM THE PUBLIC DEFENDER; AND
32 2. ONLY IF THE INDIVIDUAL WHO IS THE SUBJECT OF
33 THE RECORD HAS NOT YET RETAINED PRIVATE COUNSEL.

10 SENATE BILL 412
1 13–5903.
2 (A) THE PROGRAM SHALL ESTABLISH A COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD
3 TO MAKE:
4 (1) RECOMMENDATIONS RELATING TO THE EARLY TERMINATION OF
5 CONDITIONAL RELEASE;
6 (2) RECOMMENDATIONS RELATING TO MODIFICATION OF THE
7 CONDITIONS OF RELEASE;
8 (3) RECOMMENDATIONS RELATING TO THE EXTENSION OF
9 CONDITIONAL RELEASE;
10 (4) DECISIONS RECOMMENDATIONS RELATING TO THE ELIGIBILITY
11 OF A COMMITTED PERSON TO REMAIN ON CONDITIONAL RELEASE; AND
12 (5) DECISIONS RELATING TO ANY OUT–OF–STATE TRAVEL REQUEST.
13 (B) (1) EACH VOTING MEMBER OF THE COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD
14 SHALL BE A HEALTH CARE PROVIDER LICENSED UNDER THE HEALTH OCCUPATIONS
15 ARTICLE.
16 (2) DECISIONS OF THE COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD SHALL BE
17 DETERMINED BY A MAJORITY VOTE.
18 (3) THE COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD SHALL HAVE AN ODD
19 NUMBER OF MEMBERS.
20 (4) EACH MEMBER OF THE COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD SHALL
21 HAVE ONE VOTE.
22 (5) A COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD MAY NOT ISSUE A
23 RECOMMENDATION OR RENDER A DECISION UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS
24 SECTION UNLESS A QUORUM IS PRESENT.
25 (6) A MAJORITY OF THE MEMBERS OF THE COMMUNITY MONITORING
26 BOARD IS A QUORUM.
27 (C) (1) A COMMITTED PERSON MAY APPOINT AN AUTHORIZED AGENT TO
28 ATTEND THE ENTIRETY OF A COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD MEETING

SENATE BILL 412 11
1 CONCERNING THE COMMITTED PERSON, EXCEPT FOR THE FINAL VOTING PORTION
2 OF A MEETING.
3 (2) AN AUTHORIZED AGENT MAY BE A SOCIAL WORKER OR AN
4 INVESTIGATOR EMPLOYED BY THE COUNSEL REPRESENTING THE COMMITTED
5 PERSON.
6 (3) AN AUTHORIZED AGENT MAY ONLY GIVE AND HEAR ARGUMENTS.
7 (4) AN AUTHORIZED AGENT MAY ATTEND A COMMUNITY MONITORING
8 BOARD MEETING VIRTUALLY.
9 (D) (1) THE COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD SHALL MAINTAIN A
10 WRITTEN RECORD CONTAINING ITS FINDINGS, RECOMMENDATIONS, AND
11 DECISIONS.
12 (2) THE WRITTEN RECORD SHALL BE INCLUDED IN THE MEDICAL
13 RECORD OF THE COMMITTED PERSON.
14 (3) THE FINDINGS SHALL INCLUDE THE REASONS FOR THE
15 COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD’S RECOMMENDATION OR DECISION.
16 (E) (1) WHEN MAKING A RECOMMENDATION OR DECISION UNDER THIS
17 SECTION, THE COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD SHALL CONSIDER A WRITTEN
18 STATEMENT, IF ANY, OFFERED BY THE COMMITTED PERSON TO THE FORENSIC
19 REVIEW COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD.
20 (2) THE COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD SHALL PROVIDE NOTICE
21 TO A COMMITTED PERSON AND THE COUNSEL OF RECORD FOR THE COMMITTED
22 PERSON AS SOON AS PRACTICABLE BUT NO LATER THAN 10 DAYS BEFORE THE
23 FORENSIC REVIEW COMMUNITY MONITORING BOARD HOLDS A MEETING
24 CONCERNING THE COMMITTED PERSON.
25 (3) A COPY OF THIS NOTICE SHALL BE MAINTAINED IN THE
26 PROGRAM’S RECORDS.
27 (F) THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL MAY PROVIDE LEGAL
28 COUNSEL TO THE DEPARTMENT AT THE PROGRAM’S COMMUNITY MONITORING
29 BOARD MEETINGS.
30 (G) A COPY OF A DOCUMENT OR RECORD PRODUCED BY THE COMMUNITY
31 MONITORING BOARD UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL, ON REQUEST, BE PROVIDED TO:

12 SENATE BILL 412
1 (1) THE COMMITTED PERSON;
2 (2) COUNSEL FOR THE COMMITTED PERSON;
3 (3) THE COURT;
4 (4) THE STATE’S ATTORNEY; OR
5 (5) THE DEPARTMENT.
6 13–5904.
7 THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THIS
8 SUBTITLE.
9 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
10 October 1, 2026 2027.
